result.execSummary:
The defendant Jade D. Inderdahl was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Issue of Worthless Checks(<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.24(1).
  • Issue of Worthless Checks(<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.24(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: In the event that the Defendant is revoked or discharged from probation with outstanding financial obligations, the supervising agent shall notify the Court 10 days prior to the revocation or discharge.  A civil judgment shall be entered against the Defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement action will be used to collect the debt.

Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.
Defendant to obtain a HSED during the pendency of probation term.
Defendant to undergo an alcohol and other drug assessment and comply with any further counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.

Defendant is ordered to participate and successfully complete the Waushara County TAD/Safe Streets Program.   Defendant is to comply with any rules/recommendations as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

11:46 am cases called. 13CF20 & 15CM19. Defendant Jade D. Inderdahl in court with attorney Paul Edward Zilles.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Discussion between court and counsel.  Complaint on 15CM19 stated-Attorney Zilles confirms receipt, waives further reading- Defendant advised of minimum/maximum penalty.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea:  No Contest to Counts 1 & 2. Court accepts plea and enters JOC. Court dismisses and reads-in Count 3. Court sentences the defendant to: 13CF20- 6 months WCJ, with Huber and Good Time Credit. Credit for 109 days served. Court re-imposes cost not previously paid and to be paid within 60 days or payment plan. Court will allow civil judgment if State realizes restitution is in fact owing.  15CM19: On each count-6 months WCJ, if revoked with Huber and Good Time Credit. Consecutive to each other. No Credit for time served, STAYED and places the defendant on probation for a period of 2 years. CONDITIONS: Participate and successfully complete the Waushara TAD program,   The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician, Comply with terms of Agent. Complete HSED, AODA and follow through, Restitution $311.79, Costs to be paid within 60 days or payment plan. Appeal Rights Given.
Sentencing hearing on revocation on March 3, 2015 at 11:30 am.

13CF-20 and 15CM-19 - Both Cases Called @ 1:40 PM: Defendant Jade D. Inderdahl in court with attorney Paul Edward Zilles.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  DA argues as to SEHR 13CF-20 - argues as per Agent's recommendation.  Counsel admit receipt of Rev Order and Warrant.  No factual corrections offered.  Atty Zilles agrees with State's argument.  Statement by Def:  Yes.  The Court:  As to 13CF-20:  Court imposes 1 yr WCJ - GT and Huber - Credit for 82 days TS credit.  Balance of SEH to commence forthwith.  Costs reimposed and other unfilled obligations - 60 DTP or PP.  15CM-119:  IOWC STC:  Atty Zilles not yet appointed on this case.  DA notes that some payments under diversion program had come in to his office.  Balance of $81.57 remains owing.  State argues for plea to 1 count with concurrent probation sentence.  Defense wishes to proceed in that manner.  Off Record for Atty Zilles to confer with his client.  Back of Record at 1:43 PM:  Per Atty Zilles - Def is prepared to accept State's offer however, would like to see Def enrolled in TAD program as to new case.  Opportunity as part of supervision to complete TAD program would be beneficial to Defendant.  State would not oppose enrollment.  The Court:  Creative resolution with appropriate incentives could be offered to Def.  Court notes 188 days remain on SEHR sentence.  Suggests referral process be undertaken quickly.  Defendant will remain in Waushara Co once released.  The Court:  Vacates sentence just imposed as to 13CF-20 and both matters set aside today for referral process to proceed.  Court explains nature of commitment on Def's part for TAD program to be successful.  Sentencing hearing on revocation scheduled for March 3, 2015 at 11:30 am.
Status conference on February 4, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
Defendant is prohibited from issuing any checks for payment.
